00:29:59.970 --> 00:30:04.750
It seems to me we have one party that is now
giving us indefinite imprisonment without

00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:05.750
trial.

00:30:05.750 --> 00:30:08.700
We have another that's openly discussing the
plausibility of abolishing the Department

00:30:08.700 --> 00:30:10.100
of Education.

00:30:10.100 --> 00:30:16.210
And most interestingly, the public of the
US show willingness to vote for these nut

00:30:16.210 --> 00:30:18.620
jobs.

00:30:18.620 --> 00:30:26.951
So, in a democratic system where people are
democratically racing for the bottom, how

00:30:26.951 --> 00:30:30.610
is it that you're still standing up here and
talking about policy and not simply moving

00:30:30.610 --> 00:30:32.970
to a more sensible country?

00:30:32.970 --> 00:30:42.919
&gt;&gt;Ann Lee: I believe my sense of optimism
comes from the fact that small groups of people

00:30:42.919 --> 00:30:45.360
can affect powerful change.

00:30:45.360 --> 00:30:52.529
And that's why I started out with the story
about Deng Xiaoping and his other colleagues.

00:30:52.529 --> 00:30:57.649
And even if we look at our own history in
the United States, we've made tremendous changes

00:30:57.649 --> 00:31:01.879
and reforms, which started with small numbers
of people.

00:31:01.879 --> 00:31:03.150
And it took a long time.

00:31:03.150 --> 00:31:06.010
It took many years to abolish slavery.

00:31:06.010 --> 00:31:12.360
It took decades also to give right to vote
to women.

00:31:12.360 --> 00:31:16.320
So, you have to fight hard for them.

00:31:16.320 --> 00:31:22.049
And obviously, the folks who benefit from
the system today are going to fight hard to

00:31:22.049 --> 00:31:25.330
maintain the status quo.

00:31:25.330 --> 00:31:31.879
But if more and more people understand and
spread the word, like what happened with Occupy

00:31:31.879 --> 00:31:37.720
Wall Street, I think that it's possible.

00:31:37.720 --> 00:31:39.860
And so, that is why I remain hopeful.

00:31:39.860 --> 00:31:42.650
&gt;&gt; male #5: Hi.

00:31:42.650 --> 00:31:50.390
So, if the approval rating is so high, why
is there so much censorship by the government?

00:31:50.390 --> 00:31:56.210
They seem to be hiding things from the general
public and then Washington.

00:31:56.210 --> 00:32:00.610
So, if they are very popular, there is no
need to do something like that.

00:32:00.610 --> 00:32:02.570
So why do you think that's happening?

00:32:02.570 --> 00:32:05.980
&gt;&gt;Ann Lee: I know that often comes up.

00:32:05.980 --> 00:32:17.340
And I would say that the government's reason
to me, when I was over there as a professor,

00:32:17.340 --> 00:32:21.260
was that they were worried not so much their
own legitimacy, because they're obviously

00:32:21.260 --> 00:32:27.230
very popular, but that they worried about
people who are trying to be subversive to

00:32:27.230 --> 00:32:29.370
the government.

00:32:29.370 --> 00:32:35.929
And this is probably no different than a fear
that our government has of Al Qaida trying

00:32:35.929 --> 00:32:42.009
to subvert and recruit people into that movement.

00:32:42.009 --> 00:32:43.320
And so, what have we done?

00:32:43.320 --> 00:32:46.870
We've actually gone around killing people
like Osama bin Laden.

00:32:46.870 --> 00:32:55.279
So, I think that this perception of a national
security threat is something they view as

00:32:55.279 --> 00:33:04.139
real, just like we view that putting in X-ray
machines at all our airports is a real security

00:33:04.139 --> 00:33:08.389
threat, even though many people think it doesn't
work.

00:33:08.389 --> 00:33:17.899
So, I think it's easy for us to be judgmental
and critical about what other nations will

00:33:17.899 --> 00:33:26.990
use in terms of their policies, but if we
only hear one side of the story, it's probably

00:33:26.990 --> 00:33:32.830
not in our position to be saying they're doing
something right or wrong.

00:33:32.830 --> 00:33:39.990
But if, in terms of openness and about this
idea of censorship, I would say that yes,

00:33:39.990 --> 00:33:44.210
it would be nice to see China be more open.

00:33:44.210 --> 00:33:51.749
And the direction has actually been more open
because back 30 years ago under Mao, everything

00:33:51.749 --> 00:33:53.250
was state controlled.

00:33:53.250 --> 00:33:57.909
There was no private press, no information
from the outside.

00:33:57.909 --> 00:34:00.110
And today, it's quite different.

00:34:00.110 --> 00:34:09.070
If you go to China, there are tens of thousands
of magazines, thousands of newspapers, hundreds

00:34:09.070 --> 00:34:14.970
of thousands of books from outside of China
that get imported into China so that they

00:34:14.970 --> 00:34:23.210
can develop a very robust discourse and introduce
lots of great ideas from the outside.

00:34:23.210 --> 00:34:29.900
And when I was there in China, I had witnessed
on Chinese TV very serious debates between

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:33.230
officials about different policies.

00:34:33.230 --> 00:34:39.440
Even a friend of mine, he was also at Peking
University, named Michael Pettis, he keeps

00:34:39.440 --> 00:34:45.780
a blog on the website and he used to work
at Bear Stearns as an investment banker.

00:34:45.780 --> 00:34:52.829
And he even writes on his blog that the debates
about the currency and about many other issues

00:34:52.829 --> 00:34:57.349
are more fierce in China than even here in
the US.

00:34:57.349 --> 00:35:05.080
So, I think the censorship is probably overstated
in terms of what they do censor.

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:10.990
And I would say that some of that censorship
does happen here as well.

00:35:10.990 --> 00:35:23.730
&gt;&gt;male #6: So, in the modern era, most officials
in high office in China come from an engineering

00:35:23.730 --> 00:35:29.190
background, whereas in the US, most of them
come from a law background.

00:35:29.190 --> 00:35:34.760
How do you think this difference effects the
policies of the two countries and how can

00:35:34.760 --> 00:35:38.290
we have more engineers in US politics?

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:39.420
[laughter]

00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:46.050
&gt;&gt;Ann Lee: I'm glad you asked that question
because I published an article recently in

00:35:46.050 --> 00:35:53.559
The American Prospect addressing that idea
because not only do we want to have a more

00:35:53.559 --> 00:36:00.640
balanced legislature, it's also more immediate
in our job situation.

00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:06.490
Today, we have three million jobs that go
unfilled in the United States for six months

00:36:06.490 --> 00:36:08.050
or longer.

00:36:08.050 --> 00:36:10.990
Most of them are in technical fields.

00:36:10.990 --> 00:36:15.319
And the hiring managers and the CEOs of a
lot of these companies basically say they

00:36:15.319 --> 00:36:19.560
can't find the talent to fill them.

00:36:19.560 --> 00:36:25.770
And when you look at what kind of degrees
that college graduates are having, in 2010,

00:36:25.770 --> 00:36:32.640
over 80 thousand of them came from Performing
Arts and less than 13 thousand in Electrical

00:36:32.640 --> 00:36:33.640
Engineering.

00:36:33.640 --> 00:36:41.060
And so, we vastly need to rebalance our talent
portfolio in this country.

00:36:41.060 --> 00:36:46.930
And one of the ideas I suggested was given
that student loans can be so onerous to so

00:36:46.930 --> 00:36:55.640
many kids, why not provide the incentive of
forgiving a student if they graduate with

00:36:55.640 --> 00:37:02.210
an Engineering degree, or some other technical
degree in order to provide an economic incentive

00:37:02.210 --> 00:37:06.339
for more students to study this area?

00:37:06.339 --> 00:37:09.930
That could be one way of addressing it.

00:37:09.930 --> 00:37:20.059
And yes, the characters of debate and policies
do reflect the backgrounds of our leaders.

00:37:20.059 --> 00:37:28.579
I talk about that in one of my chapters called
"Special Economic Zones," because while our

00:37:28.579 --> 00:37:36.809
leaders can debate ad nauseum about whether
this policy is better than another policy,

00:37:36.809 --> 00:37:41.870
they do so without a lot of concrete evidence
and results.

00:37:41.870 --> 00:37:47.180
The Chinese however, basically say, "Why don't
we just test it out?"

00:37:47.180 --> 00:37:54.750
They have a very scientific approach to economic
policy, so that it's very similar to a scientist

00:37:54.750 --> 00:37:56.800
that says, "Well, we have this hypothesis.

00:37:56.800 --> 00:38:01.240
We think it will do this, but let's test it
out."

00:38:01.240 --> 00:38:03.120
And that's what the Chinese do.

00:38:03.120 --> 00:38:09.110
A lot of the results are reported by independent
observers.

00:38:09.110 --> 00:38:15.000
And then they decide whether to rule out a
policy at a national level.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:23.030
And so, if we had more of that kind of systematic
thinking about testing our policies, we might

00:38:23.030 --> 00:38:26.570
have a completely different economy at this
point.

00:38:26.570 --> 00:38:35.310
&gt;&gt;male #7: So, your idea that we set up objectives,
measure whether the objectives are achieved;

00:38:35.310 --> 00:38:37.220
it's a very alluring idea.

00:38:37.220 --> 00:38:39.710
I like it, except it's got a few major problems.

00:38:39.710 --> 00:38:42.940
One is you have to set objectives that are
achievable.

00:38:42.940 --> 00:38:45.710
You have to get consensus for the objectives.

00:38:45.710 --> 00:38:50.109
And probably the hardest, you have to actually
have measures that say, "Yes, we achieved

00:38:50.109 --> 00:38:51.109
them."

00:38:51.109 --> 00:38:53.000
Actually, "It was our policies that achieved
them rather than something that was gonna

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:54.000
happen anyway."

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:59.809
So, I wonder whether the Chinese, when they're
measuring each other, how accurate they're

00:38:59.809 --> 00:39:01.210
being.

00:39:01.210 --> 00:39:06.030
If you take something that was at Mao's level
of industrialization, not very much, let in

00:39:06.030 --> 00:39:10.470
lots of Western technology, you're gonna have
this rapid rate of industrialization.

00:39:10.470 --> 00:39:14.630
We've seen other countries with or without
very good government.

00:39:14.630 --> 00:39:19.849
So, do they know how much of the improvement
came from good government versus just letting

00:39:19.849 --> 00:39:21.670
capitalists do things?

00:39:21.670 --> 00:39:28.980
&gt;&gt;Ann Lee: Well obviously, things that happen
in an economy are very complex.

00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:32.430
And even today, many economists get those
things wrong, right?

00:39:32.430 --> 00:39:38.100
There are economic models that miss many variables.

00:39:38.100 --> 00:39:44.190
I'm not saying that that system is perfect
or that you can completely tease out whether

00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:48.290
it's just policies or some other exogenous
factor.

00:39:48.290 --> 00:39:56.030
But if you look at what happened with China
before, they started on these policies, they

00:39:56.030 --> 00:40:00.640
clearly had plenty of cheap labor that obviously
were not productive.

00:40:00.640 --> 00:40:05.150
And if you think that's the only answer, you
can still look at Africa or many other places

00:40:05.150 --> 00:40:10.869
where they are not growing and being as dynamic
as they are.

00:40:10.869 --> 00:40:16.190
So clearly, there are things they're doing
right that are making sense here.

00:40:16.190 --> 00:40:26.190
And so, I suggest that if we aren't sure,
then why don't we test it out in different

00:40:26.190 --> 00:40:27.190
areas?

00:40:27.190 --> 00:40:33.309
Our 50 states used to be called 50 laboratories
of democracy.

00:40:33.309 --> 00:40:41.690
Now, why can't we basically turn these 50
states into laboratories of economic opportunity?

00:40:41.690 --> 00:40:47.849
And there really is no harm in doing it if
the federal government and the states work

00:40:47.849 --> 00:40:53.380
closely together to come up with the right
design of trying these things out because

00:40:53.380 --> 00:40:56.850
there is no harm in just trying out and trying
to find the truth of the matter.

00:40:56.850 --> 00:40:58.210
So, I hope that--.

00:40:58.210 --> 00:40:59.490
Does that answer your question?

00:40:59.490 --> 00:41:01.210
&gt;&gt; male #7: I guess what I'm getting at--.

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:03.079
I'm not trying to actually disagree with you.

00:41:03.079 --> 00:41:06.310
